  "text": "Additional evidence supporting a relationship between anesthetics and the endogenous sleep machinery comes from experiments assessing anesthetic sensitivity following sleep deprivation. Sleep deprivation reduced the time required for sevoflurane-induced loss of righting reflex, a behavioral surrogate for loss of consciousness in animals [9 • ]. Furthermore, sensitivity to isoflurane was increased following selective REM sleep deprivation [CITATION_1] , extending the known effects of sleep deprivation in enhancing the sensitivity to anesthetics [CITATION_2] . These results demonstrate that increasing sleep drive increases sensitivity to anesthetics and support an interaction between endogenous sleep drive and anesthesia.",
